# Context

Prompt 8 showed monotonic degradation in RMSE as SEQ_LEN increased. Before concluding this is a genuine architectural limit rather than an under-training artefact, verify whether the longer-SEQ configs converged.

# Task

For each SEQ_LEN in {30, 267, 325, 372, 400}, load the saved training history (loss_history CSV or equivalent) and:

1. Plot train and val loss curves for all 5 configs on one figure (log y-axis). Annotate the best-val-epoch and stopped-epoch for each.

2. Compute for each config:
   - epochs-to-best-val
   - val loss at best epoch and at stopped epoch
   - slope of val loss over the last 10 epochs before stopping (simple linear fit)
   - whether val loss was monotonically decreasing over the last 5 epochs before stopping

3. Verdict per config:
   - "Converged" if slope over last 10 epochs is approximately zero (absolute slope < 1% of best val loss)
   - "Plateauing" if slope is small negative
   - "Still improving at stop" if slope is clearly negative (early stopping terminated prematurely)

# Interpretation

- If all configs verdict "Converged" → Prompt 8 result stands: longer windows genuinely don't help on this setup, move to Prompt 10b.
- If SEQ_LEN ≥ 267 configs verdict "Still improving at stop" → re-run those configs with patience=50 and LR schedule scaled to length. This is a 1-day retrain.
- If mixed → report per-config.

# Deliverables

1. Training-curve plot.
2. Convergence verdict per config.

# Deliverables applicable to all prompts

1. Short summary of the purpose of the prompt and the interpretation/implication of the verdict, appended to prompts/SUMMARY+CONCLUSION.txt.

# Out of scope

Anything involving retraining. This is a post-hoc analysis of existing logs only.